06118nam a22006975i 9781847420954DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20092009xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a9781847420954  a(DE-B1597)646926  a(OCoLC)646847145  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aSOC0040002bisacsh04a364.143094100aSecuring respect :bBehavioural expectations and anti-social behaviour in the UK /ced. by Andrew Millie. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of figures and tables -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes on contributors -- tIntroduction -- tRespect in context -- tRespect and the politics of behaviour -- t‘A Jekyll in the classroom, a Hyde in the street’: Queen Victoria’s hooligans -- tRespectful families and communities -- tGiving respect: the ‘new’ responsibilities of youth in the transition towards citizenship -- tEvery child matters in public open spaces -- tRespectful city living -- tDisciplining women: anti-social behaviour and the governance of conduct -- t‘The feeling’s mutual’: respect as the basis for cooperative interaction -- tRespectful city living -- tTolerance, respect and civility amid changing cities -- tRespect and city living: contest or cosmopolitanism? -- tRespect, identities and values -- tCivilising offensives: education, football and ‘eradicating’ sectarianism in Scotland -- t‘You lookin’ at me?’ Discourses of respect and disrespect, identity and violence -- tConclusions: promoting mutual respect and empathy -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver recent years, the Government focus on anti-social behaviour has been replaced by a focus on respect. Tony Blair's 'Respect Action Plan' was launched in January 2006, Gordon Brown has spoken of duty, responsibility, and respect for others, and the Conservatives have launched their 'Real Respect Agenda'. Within government, the respect agenda has a cross-departmental influence, but like anti-social behaviour before it, 'respect' has not yet been tightly defined. And what is it about the contemporary UK that sees respect as lacking, that in order to tackle anti-social behaviour we first need to 'secure respect'? Until now, there has been little attention in the academic and policy literature on the Government's push for respect. Securing respect contains ten essays from leading academics in the field that consider the origins, current interpretations and possible future for the Respect Agenda. The contributors explore various policy and theoretical discourses relating to 'respect', behavioural expectations and anti-social behaviour. The book follows the five key themes of: respect in context; young people and children; communities and families; city living; and issues of identity and values. Securing respect is inter-disciplinary, linking theory and practice, and will be of value to practitioners, academics and students with interests in criminology, socio-legal studies, social policy, urban geography, housing, social history, sociology and landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDisorderly conductxGovernment policyzGreat Britain. 0aDisorderly conductxPreventionxGovernment policyzGreat Britain. 0aDisorderly conductzGreat BritainxPrevention. 0aDisorderly conductzGreat Britain. 0aRespect for personsxGovernment policyzGreat Britain. 0aRespect for persons. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aBannister, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurney, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlint, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo